Agent’s attributes are static in our model. However, their stereo-
types and preferences evolve as they interact with others and move
through relationship phases. The social norms governing all agents
also evolve throughout the simulation. Section 3.5 details when and
how these updates to stereotypes, preferences, and norms occur.
3.2 Agents
As in all ABMs, our agents have state and can take actions. Agents’
states encompass their type, attributes, stereotypes, preferences, and
knowledge of others. The actions agents take, based on these states,
are a set of decisions, which we describe in Section 3.4.
3.2.1 Type. Agents can be of two types, and are only attracted to
agents of the opposite type. We thus loosely mimic a hetero- and
mono-normative online dating website, as was studied by Anderson
et al. [2]. We return to this limitation in our conclusion. Agents are
assigned to the two modeled types with equal probability.
3.2.2 Attributes. Each agent 𝑖 has a vector of binary attributes, 𝑎 (𝑖) .
We distinguish between race, 𝑎 (𝑖)0 , and𝐾 other attributes. Following
theory in the online dating literature [9, 19], we make two addi-
tional distinctions among attributes. First, we distinguish between
matching and competing attributes. For matching attributes, agents
try to find partners with similar values, while for the competing
attributes, they try to find partners with the highest possible values.
We assume that the protected attribute is matching.
Second, we distinguish between attributes visible only offline
as experiential attributes, and ones that are visible both online and
offline as searchable attributes. Examples of searchable attributes in-
clude personal interests and location. Sense of humor is an example
of experiential attribute [19]. Since people do not share everything
about themselves in their profiles [38], agents have a probability
of 50% to specify each searchable attribute on the platform. In the
example from Figure 1, the agent chose to specify their music taste,
but not their race. We describe the complete process of generating
attributes for new agents in the Supplementary Materials.
3.2.3 Stereotypes. Agents’ stereotypes encompass their beliefs of
which attribute combinations are more likely to be encountered [37].
We model the stereotypes of agent 𝑖 as a matrix𝐺 (𝑖) . This matrix
is initialized via a theoretically grounded model that is also based
on prior work. Specifically, when generating a new agent, we first
generate a sample of 300 agents having the same race, and 100
agents with a different race. The imbalance in sample sizes is moti-
vated by homophily: people are, in general, more likely to meet and
know people similar to themselves [46]. In addition to homophily,
we also model in-group favoritism, i.e. that people tend to look
favorably on people like them [30, 61]. To capture this in our model,
we follow prior agent-based models [35] and assume that agents
also have an initial degree of ethnocentrism. For example, as in
