The preferences of agents influence and are influenced by two
different types of social norms, i.e. sociocultural regulations on
one’s preferences [39].2 First, while interacting online, an agent
impacts and is impacted by platform norms. Second, when in an
offline relationship, the agent preferences inform and are informed
by off-platform norms. Critically, then, in our model as in the real
world [39], agent’s preferences thus vary in part based on social
norms, which change as they move between the context of the
platform and their offline social life. At the same time, norms are
aggregations of the preferences of individuals, except, as we will
discuss, when explicit efforts are made by the platform to fix norms.
Agent preferences are initialized based on a procedure common
in the decision-making literature [12]. We note here that two param-
eters govern important aspects of this process. First, a parameter 𝛽
is used to capture the level of correlation between race and other
attributes. Second, 𝛾 captures the level of correlation between the
non-protected attributes. Varying these two parameters changes
the predictability of one attribute, given another. In our virtual ex-
periment, both 𝛽 and 𝛾 are changed. Most importantly, 𝛽 is varied
to reflect different degrees to which race can be inferred by agents
based on other available attributes when the agent chooses not to
display race in their online profile.
3.2.5 Knowledge of other agents. As they interact with another
agent, agents can become aware of the values of new attributes
of that agent. This knowledge is used to make decisions about,
e.g., whether to continue relationships. How agents acquire this
knowledge is discussed in Section 3.3.
3.3 Relationship Phases
Agents can be in one of three relationship phases: 1) searching, 2)
in an online relationship, or 3) in an offline relationship.3
3.3.1 Searching phase. When first entering the platform, an agent
is in the searching phase. An agent can search in two ways. First,
the agent can perform a query for potential partners using a search
interface. Second, the agent can look through messages in their
inbox that they have received from other agents. In one turn of the
simulation, agents can perform up to 30 search actions, mimicking
the typical length of a user’s session on an online dating website
[19, 22]. A search action represents looking at either a single search
