As explained above, without any intervention, agents will filter
their searches for romantic partners by the attribute they consider to
bemost important.We refer to this baseline option as Strong filtering.
From this baseline, Hutson et al. [34] note that interventions to
reduce racial homogamy can be constructed along two dimensions.
First, we can restrict the possibility of filtering on race entirely. To
signal such an intervention we add a "non-race" label to the filter
name. Second, we can introduce diversity by showing profiles of
agents who did not provide the given attribute in their profile. We
label filtering strategies that only include the desired setting of the
given attribute as "Strong," and those that also include potential
partners who simply do not fill out a value for this attribute as
"Weak". Combining interventions on these two dimensions gives
three more filtering options, namely Strong non-race, Weak, and
Weak non-race.We also add a fourth intervention where no filtering
is allowed at all, on any attribute, i.e. the "Off" filtering option.
The five filtering conditions are most clearly stated with an
example. Consider the agents in Figure 1. Let us assume the platform
opts to use Strong filtering. Further, let us assume that the blue
agent’s strongest preference is for a romantic partner that is the
same race. In this case, the blue agent will search for others with the
same race, and will see only other potential partners who publicly
self-identified with that race on the platform. If the platform had
Weak filtering, the agent would also see any other agents who a)
have the same self-identified race or b) do not specify any race on
the platform. If the platform employed Strong non-race filtering, the
platform would not allow the agent to search by race at all. The
agent would therefore use their second strongest preference (say,
music), to perform their search. Weak non-race follows similarly,
and in the Off condition, agents would simply not be able to filter at
all. Finally, note that we have described the process with a matching
attribute; for competing attributes, agents are always assumed to
search for other agents who hold the desired attribute.
4.1.2 Attribute Intervention. Removing filtering options can make
it harder for agents to find the partners they desire. A suggested so-
lution by Hutson et al. [34] to mitigate this problem is to add or give
additional attention to new non-race attributes on which agents can
filter (e.g. political view or smoking preferences). We refer to this
intervention as anAttribute Intervention. In our model, this interven-
tion is implemented by increasing the number of dating-relevant
attributes from a baseline of 5 to a total of 9, i.e. from having one
non-racial attribute of each type, to having two of them.4
4.1.3 Norm Intervention. The final intervention from Hutson et al.
[34] that we model are attempts to change or outline platform
norms. Hutson et al. [34] suggest that different community poli-
cies, such as introducing pledges, educating users on the effect of
expressing racial preferences, and detailing the disparities faced
by racial minorities, can encourage social norms to date interra-
cially. Norms, in turn, are known to be perhaps the most powerful
mechanism for changing discriminatory behaviors [62]. In our ex-
periment, the platform norm intervention fixes the value of the
on-platform norm for the race attribute to 0. This means that agents,
via the link between norms and agent preferences, are encouraged
not to consider race at all in their decisions. Differently from the
baseline condition, when on-platform norms are updated to reflect
the average of preferences, the value on the race dimension does
not change and continues to be 0 (see the Supplemental Material).
4.2 Assumptions about Society
Table 1 lists the model parameters we vary or keep constant in
our virtual experiment. As we will show, consideration of these
parameters is critical to understanding how well claims about in-
tervention effects generalize to different assumptions about society.
At the same time, a full exploration of the parameter space is infea-
sible. We take a three-pronged approach to addressing this. First,
as noted in the table, many of these parameter and their values
are theoretically grounded and/or empirically informed by prior
work. Second, we engaged in sensitivity testing, described in the
appendix, across a range of values for all parameters. Finally, for
our virtual experiment, we fixed parameters that did not appear
to have significant impacts on model outcomes. For parameters
that did appear to have an effect, we select a default value for each
(coloured in red in Table 1); when varying one such parameter, we
keep the others at their default values.
As shown in Table 1, we vary five model parameters in our sim-
ulation. First, tolerance to unsuccessful search turns, which allows
us to see how results change if agents are more or less tolerant to
seeing undesired profiles and messages while browsing. Second,
we vary racial bias in the out-platform norms, capturing how much
importance society puts on same-race relationships compared to
the other attributes of individuals. Third, we vary the influence
norms have on preferences, i.e. the percentage of individual prefer-
ences explained by social norms. Fourth, we alter the initial degree
of ethnocentrism, which intuitively corresponds to the extent to
which agents are likely to prefer same-race relationships. The last
